'''Frances Finch, Countess of Winchilsea and Nottingham''' (c.1690 &ndash; September/October 1734),<ref name=":1"/> was an English aristocrat and social reformer.
She was the daughter of [[Basil Feilding, 4th Earl of Denbigh]], and his wife, the former Hester Firebrace.<ref name=":1">Mosley, Charles, editor. ''Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage, 107th edition, 3 volumes''. Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003, p.1087.</ref> She married [[Daniel Finch, 8th Earl of Winchilsea]] in 1720.<ref name=":1" /> There were no known children from this marriage.
Few details of her life are known; however, she was notable in being one of the aristocratic women who were early supporters of [[Thomas Coram]]'s efforts to establish a [[Foundling Hospital]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/53361054|title=Thomas Coram, Gent., 1668-1751|last=Gillian|first=Wagner,|date=2004|publisher=Boydell Press|year=|isbn=1843830574|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|pages=199; 89|oclc=53361054}}</ref> She [[Signatories to the Ladies' Petition for the Establishment of the Foundling Hospital|signed the Ladies' Petition]] which was delivered to [[George II of Great Britain|King George II]] to support the establishment of the Hospital on 25th April 1730, and she is the signatory of whom least is known.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|title=Ladies of Quality and Distinction|last=Palmer|first=Kathleen|publisher=The Foundling Museum|year=2018|isbn=|location=London|pages=8|type=Exhibition catalogue}}</ref> This group of women not only lent their prestige and respectability to the endeavour, they made it 'one of the most fashionable charities of the day'.<ref>Elizabeth Einberg, 'Elegant Revolutionaries', article in Ladies of Quality and Distinction Catalogue, Foundling Hospital, London 2018, pp. 14-15, p.15. https://foundlingmuseum.org.uk/events/ladies-of-quality-distinction/</ref> As part of an exhibition celebrating the role of women in the establishment and administration of the Hospital, called ''Ladies of Quality and Distinction'', the Foundling Museum held an exhibition in 2018 which included a family portrait of Francis.<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://foundlingmuseum.org.uk/events/ladies-of-quality-distinction/ |title=Ladies of Quality & Distinction Exhibition |website=[[Foundling Museum]] |language=en-GB |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref><ref name="Clinton">{{cite news |last1=Clinton |first1=Jane |title=Help find Foundling ‘mothers’ |url=http://camdennewjournal.com/article/help-find-foundling-mothers |accessdate=25 November 2018 |work=Camden New Journal |publisher=New Journal Enterprises |date=22 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sanderson |first1=David |title=Race to honour first ladies of charity |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/race-to-honour-first-ladies-of-charity-3qt2vw7ft |accessdate=25 November 2018 |work=The Sunday Times |publisher=Times Newspapers Limited |date=19 February 2018 |location=London, England}}</ref>
Through her marriage she was the aunt of another signatory, [[Selina Hastings, Countess of Huntingdon]].<ref name=":0" />
The cause of her death is not known. She is buried at her husband's family seat of [[Ravenstone, Buckinghamshire|Ravenstone]], Buckinghamshire.<ref name=":1"/>
