* The long vowels are considerably longer than the short vowels. The former are generally over 250 ms, whereas the latter are generally under 150 ms.{{sfnp|Visser|1997|p=14}}{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|p=9}}
* Some speakers merge the long vowels {{IPA|/iː, uː/}} with the centering diphthongs {{IPA|/iə̯, uə̯/}}.{{sfnp|Visser|1997|p=24}}
* {{IPA|/yː/}} is infrequent.{{sfnp|Visser|1997|p=19}} It and the other long close rounded vowel {{IPA|/uː/}} are absent from the dialect of Ljouwert.{{sfnp|van der Veen|2001|p=102}}
* {{IPA|/ø/}} is phonetically central {{IPAblink|ɵ}} and is quite similar to {{IPA|/ə/}}. It can be treated as its stressed equivalent.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|pp=6, 8, 10}}{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|p=11}} In phonemic transcription, many scholars<ref name="ua">For instance {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1989}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Tiersma|1999}}, {{Harvcoltxt|van der Veen|2001}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Keil|2003}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Hoekstra|Tiersma|2013}}.</ref> transcribe it with {{angbr|{{IPA|ø}}}}, but {{angbr|{{IPA|ɵ}}}} and {{angbr|{{IPA|ʏ}}}} are occasionally also used.<ref>{{angbr|{{IPA|ɵ}}}} is used by {{Harvcoltxt|Sipma|1913}} (as {{angbr|{{IPA|ö}}}}, which is how it was transcribed in 1913 - see [[History of the International Phonetic Alphabet]]), whereas {{angbr|{{IPA|ʏ}}}} is used by {{Harvcoltxt|de Haan|2010}}.</ref>
* Although they pattern with monophthongs, the long close-mid vowels transcribed {{IPA|/eː, øː, oː/}} are often realized as narrow closing diphthongs {{IPA|[ei̯, øy̑, ou̯]}}.{{sfnp|Visser|1997|pp=22–23}}{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|pp=10–11}} However, there are exceptions: for instance, speakers of the ''Hindeloopers'' dialect realize {{IPA|/øː/}} as a long monophthong {{IPAblink|øː}}.{{sfnp|van der Veen|2001|p=102}}
* Nearly all words with {{IPA|/øː/}} are loanwords from Standard Dutch.{{sfnp|Visser|1997|p=17}}
* {{IPA|/oː/}} doesn't occur before {{IPA|/s/}}.{{sfnp|Hoekstra|2001|p=86}}
* Although they pattern with monophthongs, the long open-mid vowels transcribed {{IPA|/ɛː, ɔː/}} tend to be realized as centering diphthongs {{IPA|[ɛə̯, ɔə̯]}}.{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|p=10}}{{sfnp|Visser|1997|p=23}}
* The ''Hindeloopers'' and ''Súdwesthoeksk'' dialects also feature open-mid front rounded vowels {{IPA|/{{IPA link|œ}}, {{IPA link|œː}}/}}, which are not a part of the standard language.{{sfnp|van der Veen|2001|p=102}}{{sfnp|Hoekstra|2001|p=83}}
* Many scholars<ref name="ua"/> transcribe {{IPA|/a/}} as {{IPA|/a/}}, but {{Harvcoltxt|de Haan|2010}} transcribes it as {{IPA|/ɑ/}}.{{sfnp|de Haan|2010|p=333}} Its phonetic quality has been variously described as central {{IPAblink|ä}}{{sfnp|Visser|1997|p=14}} and back {{IPAblink|ɑ}}.{{sfnp|de Haan|2010|p=333}}
* {{IPA|/aː/}} is central {{IPAblink|äː}}.{{sfnp|de Haan|2010|p=333}}{{sfnp|Visser|1997|p=14}}

=== Diphthongs ===

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;"
|+ Standard West Frisian [[diphthong]]s{{sfnp|Booij|1989|p=319}}{{sfnp|Hoekstra|2001|p=83}}
