* {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1989}} argues that the rising diphthongs {{IPA|/jɪ, jɛ, wa, wo/}} (he also lists the rare {{IPA|/jø/}}) are in fact glide-vowel sequences, not real diphthongs.{{sfnp|Booij|1989|pp=319–320}} This view is supported by {{Harvcoltxt|Hoekstra|Tiersma|2013}} who transcribe them as {{IPA|/jɪ, jɛ, wa, wo/}},{{sfnp|Hoekstra|Tiersma|2013|pp=509–510}} which is the convention used in this article.
* In Southwestern dialects, {{IPA|/wa, wo/}} are monophthongized to short central {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɞ}}, {{IPA link|ɵ}}]}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Hoekstra|2003|p=202}}, citing {{Harvcoltxt|Hof|1933|p=14}}</ref>
* The closeness of either of the elements of {{IPA|/ɛi̯/}} is somewhat variable, so that its phonetic realization is {{IPA|[æi̯ ~ æɪ̯ ~ ɛi̯ ~ ɛɪ̯]}}.{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|p=12}}
* The first element of {{IPA|/œy̑/}} is more like {{IPAblink|œ}} than {{IPAblink|ø}}.{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|p=12}} Many scholars<ref>For instance {{Harvcoltxt|Tiersma|1999}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Keil|2003}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Hoekstra|Tiersma|2013}}.</ref> transcribe this sound as {{IPA|/øy̑/}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1989}} transcribes it as {{IPA|/ʌy̑/}}, yet this article transcribes it {{IPA|/œy̑/}} to show that it is clearly distinct from the common diphthongal realization of {{IPA|/øː/}} (having a much lower starting point) and that it is virtually identical to {{IPA|/œy̑/}} in Standard Dutch.
* Some scholars<ref>For instance {{Harvcoltxt|Booij|1989}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Hoekstra|2001}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Keil|2003}}.</ref> transcribe {{IPA|/ɔu̯/}} as {{IPA|/ɔu̯/}}, yet others<ref>For instance {{Harvcoltxt|Tiersma|1999}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Hoekstra|Tiersma|2013}}.</ref> transcribe it as {{IPA|/au̯/}}. Phonetically, the first element of this diphthong may be either of these, i.e. {{IPAblink|ɔ}} or, less often, {{IPAblink|ä|a}}.{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|pp=12, 36}}
* Some varieties realize {{IPA|/ai̯/}} as {{IPA|[ɔi̯]}}.{{sfnp|Booij|1989|p=319}}
* Many speakers round the first element of {{IPA|/aːi̯/}} to {{IPAblink|ɔː}}.{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|p=12}}

