* {{IPA|/m, p, b/}} are bilabial, whereas {{IPA|/f, v/}} are labiodental.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|pp=8, 15–16}}
** {{IPA|/v/}} has two allophones: an approximant {{IPAblink|ʋ}}, which appears word-initially, and a fricative {{IPAblink|v}}, which occurs elsewhere.{{sfnp|Keil|2003|p=7}}
** In some cases, {{IPA|/d/}} alternates with {{IPA|/r/}}.{{sfnp|Keil|2003|p=8}}
** {{IPA|/r/}} is silent before other alveolar consonants.{{sfnp|Keil|2003|p=8}}{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|pp=28–29}} An exception to this rule are recent loanwords from Standard Dutch (e.g. ''sport''), which may or may not be pronounced with {{IPA|[r]}}.{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|p=29}}
* {{IPA|/ŋ, k, x, ɣ/}} are velar, whereas {{IPA|/j/}} is palatal.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|pp=8, 15–17}}
** {{IPA|/ɣ/}} has two allophones: a plosive {{IPAblink|ɡ}}, which appears word-initially and syllable-initially (the latter only when stressed), and a fricative {{IPAblink|ɣ}}, which occurs elsewhere.{{sfnp|Hoekstra|2001|p=86}}{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|pp=15, 17}}
* The syllabic sonorants {{IPA|[m̩, n̩, ŋ̍, l̩, r̩]}} occur in the following circumstances:
** In the ending {{angle bracket|en}}, which in careful speech is pronounced {{IPA|[ən]}}:{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|p=36}}
*** It is realized as {{IPA|[m̩]}} when preceded by {{IPA|/m, p, b/}}.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|p=36}}
*** It is realized as {{IPA|[n̩]}} when preceded by {{IPA|/f, v, n, t, d, s, z, r, l/}}.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|p=36}}
*** It is realized as {{IPA|[ŋ̍]}} when preceded by {{IPA|/k, x, ɣ/}}.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|p=36}}
** In the endings {{angle bracket|el}} and {{angle bracket|er}} (in careful speech: {{IPA|[əl]}} and {{IPA|[ər]}}, respectively), which after consonants are realized as {{IPA|[l̩]}} and {{IPA|[r̩]}}, respectively.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|p=36}}
** In some other cases. See {{Harvcoltxt|Sipma|1913|p=36}} for more information.
** {{IPA|/j/}} and the {{IPA|[ʋ]}} allophone of {{IPA|/v/}} are the only sonorants which cannot be syllabic.
* The sequences {{IPA|/nj, tj, dj, sj, zj/}} coalesce to {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɲ}}, {{IPA link|tɕ}}, {{IPA link|dʑ}}, {{IPA link|ɕ}}, {{IPA link|ʑ}}]}}.
* Glottal stop {{IPAblink|ʔ}} may precede word-initial vowels. In careful speech, it may also occur between unstressed and stressed vowel or diphthong.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|p=15}}
* Among fricatives, neither {{IPA|/x/}} nor any of the voiced fricatives can occur word-initially.{{sfnp|Sipma|1913|pp=16–17}}
* {{IPA|/l/}} is velarized {{IPAblink|ɫ}} in all environments except before the close front vowels {{IPA|/i, iː, y, yː/}}, where it is realized as clear {{IPAblink|l}}.

=== Final devoicing ===
Word-final {{IPA|/b, d/}} are realized as voiceless {{IPA|[{{IPA link|p}}, {{IPA link|t}}]}}.{{sfnp|van der Veen|2001|p=104}} Note, however, that final {{IPA|/b/}} is rare,{{sfnp|Tiersma|1999|p=21}} and that in loanwords from Standard Dutch, final {{IPA|/ɣ/}} can also appear, and is also devoiced to {{IPAblink|x}}.

